				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: The Perfect Bard<a name="52876"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Jul 20 04 4:41 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>There are more than a few ways to look at this. I've grouped and solo'd for my entire career so far, probably grouped more, but I made it a point to learn the tricks of swarming, AEing, chant kiting and fear kiting. In a group situation the typical bard aims to please, I think I speak clearly for the majority of us when I say that we all love to please people, bards do it well. At the same time, stretching yourself thin and trying to be the &quot;perfect bard&quot; wears you out really really fast. I understand you want to extend your own limitations and preform the best you can for a group, but you can't do it at the cost of your fun, I don't mean this as condescending but I don't need a second job, when EQ becomes that for me, I take a break. Maybe there are some people in your life who could use the same attention? It's awesome that you care so much about your duties and doing the best job you can, don't get me wrong here, but I'm trying to say that the best you do is the best you do, and if you're on the verge of cardiac arrest with carpal tunnel, sick and tired of doing everything for everyone, you're not <u>really</u> doing the best you can for yourself. 
<br />
    I found it really really easy to overextend myself as a bard. When I really started exploring bard abilities and being relied on, it felt good, I liked being told I was an exceptional puller/ccer, who doesn't? After 4 years of EQ and almost 2 years of barding, I really felt like bards fit me best because I always want to help people, it's in my nature. One important thing I forgot is that you have to help yourself too, we lose track of this far too often, a small thing here, a broken commitment there, all the while this huge amount of energy and time is going into trying to be the perfect bard, I'm not blabbing I've been through this myself, and I mean no disrespect as I said.
<br />
   One of the more important things I've learned over time is that what a man can do is not what makes him, but what a man can't do. Accept your own limitations and have great pride in what you do, this is not lazy. You can't be perfect, but you can be an awesome guy, someone everyone loves to group with, and a capable, proud bard. I gave up trying to mez 5 adds and twist heal (exaggeration) I'm all set with bending over backwards, I did it for years man, and 90% of the time, no one noticed, but they never forgot that crucial pull or expertly timed mezz. Be exact within your own limitations and don't ever let someone forget grouping with you, that's the perfect bard in my very humble opinion. 
<br />
</span></td>
