			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: The Perfect Bard<a name="52906"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Jul 20 04 7:58 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>I switch instruments while meleeing if I think that it is going to have an actively positive result. A good example of a time when not to switch an instrument is playing manasong with only the MT hurt. Here the regen you gain is more than compensated for by the melee dps you lose. Back when I used a BoH I regularly juggled 4 weapons/instruments whilst meleeing. These days it's rare, especially since I do not own a primary-hand brass instrument.
<br />

<br />
Point 2 brings me to something I posted about quite alot a few years ago. Many bards at the time would try to do <b>everything</b>. Mezzing 3 mobs while meleeing a 4th is a classic example of this. The simple truth is that bards that play this way make mistakes, and often those mistakes cause a wipe. You are also trusting to luck.
<br />

<br />
Think a moment about the situation. If you retain control of the 3 adds you win, if you lose control you lose and possibly wipe. It's absolutely obvious that the 'perfect' bard in this situation concentrates on maintaining control, and only if that control is assured do they think about something else. In the case of 3 adds the only thing that guarantees control is if they are green, and in that case you may as well just use AE songs if you really want to melee.
<br />

<br />
Most bards do use AA if they are chant kiting. In this instance the maths say that AA can add a small amount of dps. For an AE kite with 4 mobs I am unsure if the dps lost from missing an AE song would actually be less than the dps you gain from AA. Certainly if it is a gain it would be minimal, and probably compensated for by only hitting 3 mobs later because the AAed mob died sooner than the rest. And if you AE kite more than 4 mobs the chances of AA being a positive diminish even further. Not to mention, heaven forbid, the chance of missing a turn because you were changing an instrument...you still think it is worth it?
<br />

<br />
The point is that the perfect bard is one that adapts to situations and knows the limits of what they can achieve. Yesterday I did a hard adventure and I was haster, slower, cc and snarer. We got a 3-mob pull and I goto work on the mezzing. My rl partner (a cleric) starts panicking about the mob being unslowed. I get control and then throw a slow in, and go back to mezzing and hasting where resists allow.
<br />

<br />
After I chat with her about how many roles I am doing and that sometimes one of them isn't going to get done quickly. She knows this too, but it is easy to forget in the heat of the moment. The point is that if I had tried to slow before gaining control of the situation we could easily have wiped. I have to put my trust in her to do her job of keeping the MT up whilst I do my primary role, before I try to do the rest of my responsibilites.
<br />

<br />
And that is what makes a good bard. If singing just 1 song is right, a good bard will do that. If it means not performing to your personal best in order to allow the rest of the group to be optimal, that's good play too. At the end of the day what makes for a good group is one that kills as quickly as possible without any deaths. Usually the best bards are ones that achieve this without anyone else in the group really seeing them do much at all.
<br />

<br />
<img src="/skins/default/images/emotions/emotion-1.gif" border="0" alt="Smiley" hspace="2" />   Zel  <img src="/skins/default/images/emotions/emotion-1.gif" border="0" alt="Smiley" hspace="2" />
<br />
</span></td>
